This ecosystem uses brew-auth as a shared identity provider for all apps on the *.brew.rip domain. After a user logs in at auth.brew.rip, their JWT is stored in an HttpOnly cookie named brew_token scoped to .brew.rip. Every app on any subdomain (e.g. myapp.brew.rip) automatically receives this cookie on all requests — no redirect or token passing needed. The backend is responsible for reading and verifying the cookie; JavaScript cannot access it.

AUTH SERVER
  URL:          https://auth.brew.rip
  JWKS:         https://auth.brew.rip/.well-known/jwks.json
  Issuer:       https://auth.brew.rip
  Algorithm:    RS256
  Cookie name:  brew_token
  Cookie scope: .brew.rip (all subdomains)
  Expiry:       24 hours (configurable via JWT_EXPIRATION_HOURS env var)

JWT CLAIMS
  sub                       — user UUID (string)
  email                     — user email address (string)
  username                  — display name (string)
  role                      — "super_admin", "admin", or "user" (string)
  password_change_required  — true if user must change password on next login (boolean)
  iss                       — "https://auth.brew.rip"
  iat / exp                 — issued at / expiration timestamps

VERIFYING THE TOKEN IN A NEW APP'S BACKEND
  1. Read the brew_token cookie from the incoming request (NOT the Authorization header).
  2. Fetch the JWKS from https://auth.brew.rip/.well-known/jwks.json to get the public key.
     Use the kid in the JWT header to select the correct key from the JWKS keys array.
     Cache the JWKS with a reasonable TTL (e.g. 10 minutes) to avoid hammering the auth server.
  3. Verify the JWT signature using RS256 with the retrieved public key.
  4. Validate: issuer == "https://auth.brew.rip", expiration is in the future.
  5. Extract claims from the verified payload.

  Node.js example using jwks-rsa + jsonwebtoken:
    const jwksRsa = require('jwks-rsa');
    const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');
    const client = jwksRsa({ jwksUri: 'https://auth.brew.rip/.well-known/jwks.json', cache: true });
    function getKey(header, cb) {
      client.getSigningKey(header.kid, (err, key) => cb(err, key?.getPublicKey()));
    }
    jwt.verify(req.cookies.brew_token, getKey, { algorithms: ['RS256'], issuer: 'https://auth.brew.rip' }, (err, decoded) => { ... });

  Express — also add cookie-parser middleware:
    const cookieParser = require('cookie-parser');
    app.use(cookieParser());

REDIRECTING UNAUTHENTICATED USERS
  If no cookie / invalid token, redirect to:
    https://auth.brew.rip/login?return_url=<current full URL>
  brew-auth will redirect back to return_url after successful login.
  Only accept return_url values that start with https:// (prevent open redirect).

CREATING USER ACCOUNTS

  Accounts are invite-only. The flow is:
    1. A super_admin or admin sends an invite via POST /api/users/invite.
       This emails the user a registration token.
    2. The user visits the registration link, which calls POST /api/auth/register
       with the token + their chosen username + password.

  POST /api/auth/login
    Body: { "email": "...", "password": "..." }
    Response: { "token": "...", "passwordChangeRequired": false }
    Also sets the brew_token cookie. The token in the response body is the same JWT.

  POST /api/auth/register  (complete an invitation)
    Body: { "token": "<invite token>", "username": "...", "password": "..." }
    Response: { "token": "...", "passwordChangeRequired": false }
    Sets the brew_token cookie.

  POST /api/users/invite  (requires valid JWT cookie, role admin or super_admin)
    Body: { "email": "...", "role": "user" | "admin" }
    Roles: super_admin can invite admin or user. admin can only invite user. Cannot invite super_admin.
    Sends an email via Resend with a registration link.

  GET /api/auth/me  (requires valid JWT cookie)
    Returns: { "id": "...", "email": "...", "username": "...", "role": "..." }

  POST /api/auth/logout  (requires valid JWT cookie)
    Clears the brew_token cookie.

  POST /api/auth/change-password  (requires valid JWT cookie)
    Body: { "currentPassword": "...", "newPassword": "..." }

  GET /api/users  (requires valid JWT cookie, role admin or super_admin)
    Returns list of all users.

SUPER ADMIN ACCOUNT
  Created automatically on first startup from the SUPER_ADMIN_EMAIL and
  SUPER_ADMIN_PASSWORD env vars set during Beachhead's Configure Auth flow.
  The super admin has role "super_admin" and can invite admins and users.
  On first login the super admin may be prompted to change their password
  (password_change_required claim will be true).

ROLES
  super_admin — full access, can invite admin and user, can manage all users
  admin       — can invite users, can manage non-admin users
  user        — standard access, no user management

ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES (Beachhead side)
  AUTH_JWKS_URL=https://auth.brew.rip/.well-known/jwks.json
  AUTH_ISSUER=https://auth.brew.rip
  AUTH_COOKIE_NAME=brew_token
  These are written automatically by the "Configure Auth" + "Activate Auth"
  bootstrap flow in the Beachhead dashboard.
